It would be great to shows date field such as response time vs issue type field in two dimensional gadget.

It seems that at least at some point in time, the Date custom fields (not DateTime) were stored using a time zone difference based on the current logged user.

You can find all invalid records by running:
{code}
select id, datevalue 
from customfieldvalue
where customfield IN (select id from customfield where customfieldtypekey = 'com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:datepicker') AND
( extract(minute from datevalue) != 0 OR extract(hour from datevalue) <> 0 ) and extract(hour from datevalue)  < 12;
{code}

And here is a fix that is supposed to remove the time information from these records. Be careful that truncation is ok only for ~50% of them, for others you need to add a day.

{code}
update customfieldvalue SET datevalue = date_trunc('day', datevalue) 
where customfield  IN (select id from customfield where customfieldtypekey = 'com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:datepicker') AND
( extract(minute from datevalue) != 0 OR extract(hour from datevalue) <> 0 ) and extract(hour from datevalue)  < 12 ;

update customfieldvalue SET datevalue = date_trunc('day', datevalue) + interval '1' day
where customfield IN (select id from customfield where customfieldtypekey = 'com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:datepicker') AND
( extract(minute from datevalue) != 0 OR extract(hour from datevalue) <> 0 ) and extract(hour from datevalue)  > 12 ;
{code}

This is related to the fact the Date custom fields are using DateTime database fields. Now. the big surprise was that in the import process the timezone difference was applied to the datetime value instead of being kept separate (+xx suffix).

I found more than 5000 such errors, and all of them seem to have happened while importing via CSV. I tried to replicate the bug using issue edit but it seems that in this case it does save the correct value, without timezone.

Note: this bug was raised against JIRA because you need to add a database fixation step in order to fix invalid data that is already existing in current deployments.

This bug is important because it does affect indexing and searching, and you may be unable to find a record based on the date, just because of a time-zone difference (in reality dates do not have time zones, only datetime can have timezones).

We have an add-on ([Configuration Manager for JIRA|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/plugins/com.botronsoft.jira.configurationmanager]) which provides functionality for automatic roll-out of configuration changes from one JIRA instance to another. Such roll-outs usually perform large number of changes to the JIRA configuration (projects, workflows, custom fields, users, etc).

After configuration changes are made, we trigger an event so that all caches are cleared to ensure that there are no stale configuration objects in JIRA's caches:
{code}
getEventPublisher().publish(ClearCacheEvent.INSTANCE);
{code}

Recently, a customer reported incompatibility with Arsenale Dataplane add-on - after every deployment with our tool, Dataplane would delete its index, requiring the administrator to trigger a rebuild which takes hours. This effectively makes our tool unusable in this environment.

It looked like Dataplane was listening for XMLRestoreFinishedEvent, which is supposed to be triggered whenever a database backup was restored.

However, in com.atlassian.jira.user.util.UserUtilImpl there is the following piece of code:
{code}
    @EventListener
    public void onClearCache(final ClearCacheEvent event)
    {
        flushUserCaches();
    } 

    public void flushUserCaches() 
    {
        activeUsersCount.removeAll();
        // Fire a Crowd Embedded XMLRestoreFinishedEvent to clear Crowd caches.
        eventPublisher.publish(new XMLRestoreFinishedEvent(this));
    } 
{code}

So UserUtilImpl clears its own cache *and sends an XMLRestoreFinishedEvent*. An action which, I presume, is based on the (failed) assumption that ClearCacheEvent can only be triggered when a database backup is restored. This kind of coupling is not really logical.

Given the fact that EventPublisher and ClearCacheEvent are both API and any add-on is able to trigger events, this behavior contradicts with the official documentation ([JIRA-Specific Atlassian Events|https://developer.atlassian.com/display/JIRADEV/JIRA-Specific+Atlassian+Events]) which states that XMLRestoreFinishedEvent is "Thrown when an XML backup is finished being restored."

Please fix this, as it may be a cause for many incompatibilities between add-ons and will be extremely difficult to work-around.

